The paper deals with anonymizing physical activity data, which is a type of health data. This suggests that it could belong to the cs.DB (databases) sub-category, which deals with data management and privacy. Additionally, the paper proposes a new approach for anonymization, which could fall under the cs.CY (computational geometry) sub-category, which deals with clustering and data analysis. The paper also mentions the high privacy risks associated with publishing physical activity data, which could place it under the cs.CR (cryptography and security) sub-category. The proposed approach involves reducing computational costs, which could fall under the cs.IR (information retrieval) sub-category, which deals with efficient data processing. Finally, the paper involves data analysis and machine learning techniques, which could place it under the cs.LG (machine learning) sub-category.
